# ============================================================================
# BK4 LLA — Lesson 3A (new 5-type format) — validation conversion
# Conventions: $PRODUCE uses RESPONSE; $DIALOGUE listen-then-repeat marked REPEAT;
# blank line between items; LINEs kept short (1-2 sentences) for snappy audio.
# ============================================================================

$MODULE
DIOCO_DOC_ID: lc_alc_lla_bk4_l3a
TITLE: ALC Book 4 — Lesson 3A: Clothes and Uniforms
DESCRIPTION: Clothing vocabulary, wear/put on/take off, and past tense.
TARGET_LANG_G: en
HOME_LANG_G: en
VOICE_DEFAULT: aoede | Clear, friendly American English narrator
VOICE: Collins | achernar | Male officer, matter-of-fact
VOICE: Andrews | achird | Male officer, relaxed

$LESSON Lesson 3A

# --- Figure 1a: vocabulary + paragraphs (listen, then repeat) ---
$DIALOGUE Figure 1: Clothes
REPEAT
INTRO: Look at the picture and repeat the words and sentences.
INSTRUCTION: Listen and repeat.

VOCAB: wear / wore
LINE: Capt Collins wears his uniform to work. He wore a necktie today. {page_045_001.jpg} {bk04-l3a-f1-01.mp3}

LINE: He doesn't wear a tie every day. He wears his name tag on his shirt.

LINE: He has six of these shirts. He's wearing a new belt, and he has a new hat, too.

VOCAB: takes off
VOCAB: puts on
VOCAB: clothes
LINE: After work, Capt Collins takes off his uniform and puts on civilian clothes.

LINE: Today he took off his uniform before dinner. Then he put on a T-shirt and old pants.

# --- Figure 1b: answer the questions (same figure -> second activity) ---
$PRODUCE Figure 1: Answer the questions
INTRO: Listen to each question and answer out loud, then check.
INSTRUCTION: Answer, then check.

PROMPT: Does Capt Collins wear his uniform to work?
RESPONSE: Capt Collins wears his uniform to work.

PROMPT: Does he wear a tie every day?
RESPONSE: He doesn't wear a tie every day.

PROMPT: Where does Capt Collins wear his name tag?
RESPONSE: Capt Collins wears his name tag on his shirt.

PROMPT: How many of these shirts does he have?
RESPONSE: He has six of these shirts.

PROMPT: When does Capt Collins take off his uniform?
RESPONSE: Capt Collins takes off his uniform after work.

PROMPT: What did he put on then?
RESPONSE: Then he put on a T-shirt and old pants.

# --- Figure 2: true / false (audio statements) ---
$SELECT Figure 2: True or False?
INTRO: Listen to each statement and decide if it is true or false.
INSTRUCTION: Tap True or False.
OPTION: t | True
OPTION: f | False

PROMPT: A cap is a hat. {bk04-l3a-f2-01.mp3}
ANSWER: t
# +AUDIO per item below

PROMPT: Uniforms are clothes.
ANSWER: t

PROMPT: Trousers are pants.
ANSWER: t

PROMPT: Ties and belts are the same.
ANSWER: f
FEEDBACK: Ties and belts are not the same.

PROMPT: Ties and neckties are different.
ANSWER: f
FEEDBACK: Ties and neckties are the same.

# --- Figure 3: dialog (listen, then repeat; role-play part dropped) ---
$DIALOGUE Figure 3: At the Restaurant
REPEAT
INTRO: Listen to the conversation, then repeat it.
INSTRUCTION: Listen and repeat.

Collins: Did you wear your uniform to the restaurant?

Andrews: No, I wore civilian clothes last night.

Collins: Did you wear a necktie?

Andrews: Yes, I put on a tie. I took it off after dinner.

Collins: What did Larry wear?

Andrews: He wore a T-shirt, pants, and a hat.

Collins: Was the hat his old baseball cap?

Andrews: Yes, and he didn't take it off inside.

# --- Figure 4: same / different minimal pairs ---
$SELECT Figure 4: Same or Different?
INTRO: Listen to the two words. Are they the same or different?
INSTRUCTION: Tap Same or Different.
OPTION: s | Same
OPTION: d | Different

PROMPT: wed ... red {bk04-l3a-f4-01.mp3}
ANSWER: d
# +AUDIO per item below

PROMPT: wake ... wake
ANSWER: s

PROMPT: west ... rest
ANSWER: d

PROMPT: rose ... rose
ANSWER: s

PROMPT: wave ... wave
ANSWER: s

PROMPT: weighs ... raise
ANSWER: d

PROMPT: wipe ... ripe
ANSWER: d

PROMPT: read ... read
ANSWER: s

PROMPT: reed ... weed
ANSWER: d

PROMPT: went ... rent
ANSWER: d

# --- Figure 5: sound discrimination /w/ vs /r/ ---
$SELECT Figure 5: /w/ as in "went" or /r/ as in "rent"?
INTRO: Listen to each word. Tap a for the /w/ sound or b for the /r/ sound.
INSTRUCTION: Tap the sound you hear.
OPTION: a | /w/ — as in "went"
OPTION: b | /r/ — as in "rent"

PROMPT: week {bk04-l3a-f5-01.mp3}
ANSWER: a
# +AUDIO per item below

PROMPT: want
ANSWER: a

PROMPT: radio
ANSWER: b

PROMPT: room
ANSWER: b

PROMPT: walk
ANSWER: a

PROMPT: report
ANSWER: b

PROMPT: always
ANSWER: a

PROMPT: razor
ANSWER: b

PROMPT: correct
ANSWER: b

PROMPT: window
ANSWER: a
